{{About|the malware|backoff in computer networking|exponential backoff}} [[File:Backoff_Malware.jpg|thumb|Backoff Malware]] '''Backoff''' is a kind of [[malware]] that targets [[point of sale]] (POS) systems.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.us-cert.gov/ncas/alerts/TA14-212A |title= About Backoff Malware |accessdate=2014-07-31 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://securebox.comodo.com/pos-system/backoff-malware |title= Backoff Malware complete overview |accessdate=2014-07-31 }}</ref> It is used to steal [[credit card]] data from Point of Sale machines at [[Retail#Types by marketing strategy|retail stores]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jameslyne/2014/08/26/backoff-malware-hits-1000-businesses-credit-card-machines-and-target/#2515c7ea5af4 |title= Backoff malware hits credit card machines |accessdate= 2014-08-26 }}</ref> [[Cyber crime|Cybercriminals]] use Backoff to gather data from credit cards. It is installed via remote desktop type applications where POS systems are configured.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://whatis.techtarget.com/definition/Backoff |title= Backoff Malware used by Cybercriminals }}</ref> It belongs to the [[Point-of-sale malware|POS Malware]] family as it is known to [[Memory-scraping malware|scrape the memory]] of POS devices.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tripwire.com/state-of-security/incident-detection/backoff-pos-malware-are-you-infected-and-dont-know-it/ |title= Backoff malware-WHAT IS IT?|accessdate= 2014-08-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://static1.squarespace.com/static/555fc02fe4b0767a7f081cfa/t/5615b66ee4b065af7af69daf/1444263534871/wp-Backoff+Analysis+White+Paper+2014+V3.pdf |title= Memory Scrapping malware – Biggest Threat To the Retail|format= PDF | accessdate= 2014-01-03 }}</ref>
==Operation== Backoff malware injects the malicious stub into the [[File Explorer|explorer.exe]] file to gain access to the POS machines and it scrapes the victim's machine memory from running the [[Process (software)|processes]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://info.rippleshot.com/blog/backoff-point-sale-malware-need-know |title= Know About Point of Sale Malware |accessdate=2014-09-08}}</ref> It searches this memory for leftover credit card data after a payment card has been swiped.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2838732/the-backoff-malware-linked-to-data-breaches-is-spreading.html|title=The 'Backoff' malware used in retail data breaches is spreading PCWorld}}</ref> Cybercriminals have mutated different variants of Backoff while some of the variants are equipped with [[keylogging]] functionality.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.scmagazine.com/new-version-of-backoff-detected-malware-variant-dubbed-rom/article/381054/|title= Backoff Malware Variants |accessdate= 2014-11-03 }}</ref> Some of the Backoff variants have C2 component which helps the malware to upload the victim's personal data, download the malware onto the victim POS machine and to uninstall the malware.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bankinfosecurity.in/pos-malware-still-works-a-8044|title= Functionality of Backoff Malware |accessdate= 2015-04-06}}</ref>
==Incidents== Backoff Malware was aggressive and about 16.2% been infected in the third quarter of 2014. The survey by Department of Homeland Security(DHS) states that about thousands of businesses have been infected by Backoff POS Malware.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cse.wustl.edu/~jain/cse571-14/ftp/pos_security/index.html|title= Survey of Backoff Malware}}</ref>
Network security company Damballa records a 57 percent infection increase from Backoff malware during August 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.damballa.com/q3-state-infections-report-reveals-57-increase-backoff-malware-august-september/|title=Q3 State of Infections Report Reveals 57% Increase in Backoff Malware from August to September - Damballa|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref> Big companies like Home Depot, Target and Dairy Queen suffered from backoff infection and many more smaller companies may be infected.
