{{cleanup|date=July 2014|reason=Not organized and lacks structure}} '''Granville Seward Austin''' (1927 – 6 July 2014) was an American historian of the [[Indian Constitution]].<ref name="vedam">{{cite web |title=Working a Democratic Constitution : The Indian Experience |url=http://www.vedamsbooks.com/no15421.htm |publisher=Vedam Books |accessdate=January 27, 2009}}</ref><ref name="oup">{{cite web |title=Working a Democratic Constitution : The Indian Experience |url=http://www.oup.com/us/catalog/general/subject/Law/ConstitutionalLaw/?view=usa&ci=9780195648881 |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=2008-01-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080328222321/http://www.oup.com/us/catalog/general/subject/Law/ConstitutionalLaw/?view=usa |archivedate=2008-03-28 |df= }}</ref>
==Education== Austin received most of his early education at Norwich, Vermont, USA. Austin graduated from Dartmouth College with a BA in American Literature.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} He then earned a doctorate in Modern Indian History from Oxford University.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}
==Career== He worked as a journalist/photographer and later served with the U. S. Information Service, Department of State, Department of Health, Education and Welfare, and on the staff of a U. S. senator. He has held fellowships or grants from St. Antony's College, Oxford, the Ford Foundation, the Fulbright Program, the American Institute of Indian Studies, the Rockefeller Foundation, the Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars, the Rajiv Gandhi Foundation, and the Institute of Current World Affairs.<ref name="Austin">{{Cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Granville Austin - About the Author | work = | publisher = granvilleaustin.com | date = | url = http://www.granvilleaustin.com/Austin.htm | doi = | accessdate = 10 April 2012}}</ref>
Austin is the author of two seminal political histories of the constitution of India, ''The Indian Constitution: Cornerstone of a Nation'' and ''Working a Democratic Constitution: The Indian Experience''.<ref name="oup" />
Granville Austin died on 6 July 2014<ref>{{cite web | url=http://lawandotherthings.blogspot.in/2014/07/granville-austin-rip.html | title=Granville Austin, RIP | publisher=Vikram Raghavan | date=7 July 2014 | website=Law and other things}}</ref> and is survived by his four children, three grandchildren, and his wife, Nancy Austin, in Washington, D. C.<ref name="Austin" />
==Awards== In 2011, in recognition for his writing on the framing and working of the Indian Constitution, Granville Austin was awarded a [[Padma Shri]] award, the fourth highest civilian honor of the [[Republic of India]].<ref name="NIC">{{Cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Padma Sri Awardees | work = | publisher = NIC - Govt. of India | date = | url = http://india.gov.in/myindia/padmashri_awards_list1.php?start=80 | format = | doi = | accessdate = 10 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Padma Awards Announced|url=http://www.pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx?relid=69364|publisher=[[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] |date=25 January 2011|accessdate=25 January 2011}}</ref> [[National Translation Mission]] of the Ministry of Human Resource Development of the Government of India has selected ''The Indian Constitution: Cornerstone of a Nation'' for translation into Indian languages. The book has already been published in [[Telugu language|Telugu]], [[Marathi language|Marathi]], [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]], [[Odia language|Odia]], [[Hindi language|Hindi]] and [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] languages.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Published Translations & Dictionaries|url=http://www.ntm.org.in/languages/english/publicationdetails.aspx|publisher=[[National Translation Mission]] |date= |accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref>
